{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14036"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14036"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.54,0.11,0.11,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6685"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92037"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking help to quit smoking. She has been smoking 20 cigarettes per day for the past 12 years and has attempted to quit twice before without success. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She expresses a strong desire to quit and is willing to try pharmacological aids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the least preferred recommendation for smoking cessation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nicotine patch","Sertraline","Bupropion","Varenicline","Combination nicotine patch and gum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E is an antidepressant that is not indicated for smoking cessation. There is no evidence to support its use as a pharmacological aid for quitting smoking, and it is not recommended in current guidelines for this purpose. Its use would not address nicotine dependence or withdrawal symptoms and would not be expected to improve quit rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENicotine patch\u003C/strong\u003E is a form of nicotine replacement therapy (NRT). While it can be an effective and safe option for smoking cessation, it is generally less effective than varenicline when used alone. Nicotine patches provide a steady, long-acting dose of nicotine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBupropion\u003C/strong\u003E is an antidepressant that has been shown to be effective in helping people cease smoking. This drug works by reducing cravings and withdrawal symptoms, possibly through its effects on dopamine and noradrenaline neurotransmission. While effective, it is generally considered less effective than varenicline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVarenicline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective medication to help with smoking cessation. It is a partial agonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. This action helps reduce cravings and withdrawal symptoms while also decreasing the rewarding effects of smoking. Various studies have shown that varenicline is more effective than other single agents in achieving long-term smoking cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombination nicotine patch and gum\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective approach that combines long-acting and short-acting forms of NRT. This combination is more effective than single NRT products and may be comparable to varenicline in some studies. However, most evidence still suggests that varenicline has a slight edge in effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that while varenicline is the most effective option, the choice of smoking cessation aid should be tailored to the individual, taking into consideration factors such as past experiences, preferences, contraindications, and potential side effects. All pharmacological aids should be used in conjunction with behavioural support and counselling for the best chances of successful smoking cessation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Varenicline is the most effective pharmacological agent for smoking cessation.","Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) is a safe and effective option for smoking cessation.","Sertraline is not an effective pharmacological aid for smoking cessation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Overview of drug therapy for tobacco smoking and nicotine dependence [Internet]. (AU): eTG; 2023 [updated 2023; cited 4th August 2024] Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Addiction%20Medicine\u0026topicfile=alcohol-drug-problems\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_AMG_Overview-of-tobacco-smoking-and-nicotine-dependence_topic_6#c_AMG_Overview-of-tobacco-smoking-and-nicotine-dependence_topic_6","Lindson N, Theodoulou A, Ord\u00f3\u00f1ez-Mena JM, Fanshawe TR, Sutton AJ, Livingstone-Banks J, et al. Pharmacological and electronic cigarette interventions for smoking cessation in adults: component network meta\u2010analyses. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2023;9:CD015226. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD015226.pub2. Available at: https://www.cochranelibrary.com/cdsr/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD015226.pub2/full"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14036"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T17:35:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T17:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6685"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2355"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc89","name":"Addiction Medicine","synonyms":["Drug \u0026 Alcohol Medicine"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-06-06T01:28:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-06T01:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4952"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Addiction Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4988"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Population Health and the Context of General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:40:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:40:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"12"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11624"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Addictive Behaviours (ADD)","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positio